'''Earl Alfred Jinkinson''' (d. November 30, 1995 in [[Tryon, North Carolina]]) was an American antitrust lawyer. ==Biography== Jinkinson received his law degree from [[Stetson University]], after which he became an [[FBI]] agent in 1941. He worked for the [[United States Department of Justice]] (DOJ) as chief of their antitrust division in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], [[Florida]] from 1948 to 1952, whereupon he began working at their [[Chicago]] division.<ref name=trib/> He later became the chief of this anti-trust division.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=1955-05-28 |title=U.S. Skeds New Hearings in Juke Anti-Trust Case |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA92 |magazine=Billboard |page=92}}</ref> While in charge of the DOJ's Chicago antitrust office, he led cases against [[Seeburg Corporation]]<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=1956-08-04 |title=U.S. Antitrust Investigation Called Off |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iQoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA109 |magazine=Billboard |page=109}}</ref> and the ''[[Kansas City Star]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1955/01/16/page/188/article/open-u-s-trial-of-kansas-city-star-this-week |title=Open U.S. Trial of Kansas City Starts This Week |agency=Chicago Tribune |page=32|date=1955-01-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Yl5NJhHP5HYC |title=Boss-busters & Sin Hounds: Kansas City and Its Star |last=Haskell |first=Harry |publisher=University of Missouri Press |year=2007 |pages=365–6, 376|isbn=9780826266125 }}</ref> He later joined [[Winston & Strawn]], where he went on to become a senior partner. While there, he handled antitrust cases including one involving the [[Milwaukee Braves]], in which he served as lead counsel.<ref name=trib/> He retired from Winston & Strawn in 1988.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4311474.html | title=Earl A. Jinkinson, Senior Law Partner | work=Chicago Sun-Times | date=29 November 1995 | accessdate=21 April 2017}}</ref> ===Personal life=== Jinkinson was married to Virginia Jinkinson (née Watson) until his death in 1995. They had two daughters: [[Georgia Bonesteel]] and Jill Moore.<ref name=trib>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-11-30/news/9511300183_1_winston-strawn-antitrust-du |title=Prosecutor, Lawyer Earl Jinkinson |last=Heise |first=Kenan |website=Chicago Tribune |publication-date=30 November 1995}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.blueridgenow.com/news/20050610/virginia-w-jinkinson-93 |title=Virginia W. Jinkinson, 93 |website=BlueRidgeNow.com |publication-date=10 June 2005}}</ref>
